{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9c34a66a-a787-4b4d-8020-33f073c86c39","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance for macOS crash dump recovery without `createdump`:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS (NativeAOT, no `createdump`)\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — run your app. macOS will write a core file (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking it. You may need to:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n5. **Check Apple's Crash Reporter logs** at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces even without core dumps.\n\n6. **Analyze the core file** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n7. **Load the SOS/DAC plugin** (if available for NativeAOT) or use native `lldb` commands (`bt`, `frame variable`, etc.) to inspect the crash.\n\n**Key note:** NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` because they don't include the CoreCLR runtime. You rely on the OS-level core dump mechanism instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a1ff9c1c-62d5-4828-b6fd-82b93ccf362d","outputTokens":389,"requestId":"5032:5409:26E2F5:30B842:69F554E0"},"id":"ecd8d947-5d9c-4e53-a652-81a392512f83","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:35:38.324Z","parentId":"813dcbec-332c-4d71-875f-bacc1dfb76ba"}
